United States: Repetition Is Mother of Wisdom · Global Voices
It even becomes comical, the tireless effort with which Barack Obama, president of the reputation of wise, reproduces his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered to be quite simple.
When he ended up letting his doctrine sweat so eagerly awaited, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush's Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending further reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by the civil war as being "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which came from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed so much that the newspapers at present do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, however, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a much more favourable final situation than one could expect.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reticence despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months but, in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to extirpate the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally had 10 000.
What brings the most problems to Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this whole process within three years. Obama's whole doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half increase will bring the same benefits as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be relied on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their leadership on a day-to-day basis, depending on what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing but powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is singularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity in the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "early-to-act state", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The temporal horizon of Obama's strategy is perplexed by his voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of reality can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war with a view to their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the will of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not affect Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult issue of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
This will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
Obama's only rustin is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to plan on a new strategy, in case it proves to be a total fiasco.
