Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococcals will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already rising, saying that compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines for vaccines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay.
Specialists also see clearly in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for August children.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal diseases.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If vaccination started last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th months of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
Yet the parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Specialists estimate that each year sickness insurance spends 300 to 450,000 kroons in vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far, the State has spent approximately 500,000 crowns per year on all immunization of children.
The vaccination reimbursed was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococcals cause inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years of age due to pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced the reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions on a possible obligation to immunise in the future.
From January, it must be paid by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský said that compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to have been able to impose this at least.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed, Kalovský said.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We do not envisage it at all for the time being, said its spokesman Vlastimil Srše
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Paediatric Society, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, one could consider a decrease in vaccination renewals "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional", says Cabrnochová.
Specialists expect that as of next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Vaccination against pneumococcals is also a break because it is the first vaccination of children that is financed by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should free up funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their own products
This, however, is linked to the concerns of paediatricians in practice, which concern the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have the vaccines purchased by the insurance companies, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products supplied by the state.
However, some Members were concerned that this would allow insurance to "deduct the sums from health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
It is estimated that paediatricians will have to individually invest nearly 40,000 crowns per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It won't be easy, according to Cabrnochová.
