Written in the constitution of the country in 1978, the Chinese policy of the single child is, without a doubt, the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay colossal fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and face discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have given the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the execution of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority forced pregnant women of a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys to girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the single child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007, they softened many of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Beijing University, said central government authorities recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive birth promotion campaign.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of detailed regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city's government has sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their homes and slip leaflets under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the family planning officer, the response was disappointing.
Dissatisfaction
Although officials in a rural city in the suburbs of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in applications from couples wishing to have a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there is no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly more than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the family planning committee in the municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly consider the policy of the single child to be a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the first child of the couple.
It's true, we're being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she wanted only one child because she was one herself. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us."
We don't have the habit of taking care of someone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company says it more seriously.
For couples working two, middle class, who lower the birth rate, he says, one must be selfish if it is to succeed.
People aged 20 or 30 grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and do not want to have this lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even one child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space problems -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, says Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to enjoy a higher standard of living, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned to the spotlight on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden, in the coming times.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it informed the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that are running out of time, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not say how rich countries would give to the poor to withstand global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Sierra Club's representative in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary General described on climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the complete picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent of 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched the negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
On Friday, however, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Climate Negotiator, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the main developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister, He Yafei, said that the US main negotiator, either lacked "good sense", or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not help China financially to combat global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the main powers were struggling to find out who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters responsible for their actions.
It is really a game in which is developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that the negotiations will lead at least to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a 24-page treaty, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states "has put political pressure on the complete political process", partly because they are now unified and they are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the need to resolve most of the outstanding issues before Heads of Government reached agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister descended from their aircraft and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend in-house meetings and information conferences, so that they could make claims that will be considered in the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the Congress Centre every day -- guitar player activists present nocturnal shows mocking the countries that they believe are betraying and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the courtyard of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice-president for global policy of Conservation International.
The heavy goods vehicles are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 225 km/h will redefine Monday's syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. Monday morning, a whistle will break through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transport revolution in Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, while travelling from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering the 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes on board the first commuter train Javelin outside London.
He hoped that the new service would allow Britain to integrate an international network of fast and reliable trains and would link the major conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The small lost holes will become thriving suburban cities, business travel will be much shorter and the passage of the aircraft and car to the train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable planning battle and the fears of environmental dangers risk curbing British high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will deliver its document to Lord Adonis on December 30th.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new London-West Midlands line will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where environmental impact can be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up up to 25 meters from the final itinerary.
It is also expected that HS2 will present three options for a larger, northward high-speed network.
Lord Adonis will answer in spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two to or near Birmingham, with a branch going west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going north-east, to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the best performance option" said a rail professional.
When this is over, travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400 km/h, making the British network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains of 400m long and capable of carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a London - Birmingham line.
A terminal that can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be required.
Given the space constraints, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high-speed network.
Rail industry experts state that only St Pancras International or Euston offers this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should be put in place, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken before a general election.
Even if it starts the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
First of all, trains will be forced to run off high-speed lines on existing rails north of Birmingham, maintaining journey times between London and Scotland in excess of three hours.
This solution seems to be the best way to ensure a passage from aircraft to trains, which is a reference point for the rail revolution.
Taxpayers repay GBP 75,000 loan for Tory Orangery
Alan Duncan, the main member of Parliament Tory, had the taxpayer pay thousands of pounds a year to pay back the cost of an orangery he built in his home in his riding.
The leader of the party who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that the members of parliament were "stored", increased his loan by GBP 75,000 to build an oak extension to his second house in Rutland.
He had been authorized to charge the taxpayer for the additional interest, amounting to hundreds of pounds a month.
The Commons authorities received the complaints at that time and were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who conducted a control of members' expenses. Last night, Mr. Duncan stated that the complaints could not be "clearer or simpler".
Duncan, one of the richest members of parliament, owns a two-storey house in a village in his constituency of Rutland - Melton.
The surrounding houses were sold for almost £1 million.
The ground floor includes a kitchen, a living room and a dining room, but the emoluments office says Mr. Duncan needed more space.
Last year he added a veranda to the house, describing it in his plans as an orange grove.
Neighbors describe her as a "veranda for pleasure".
Mr. Duncan was not asked to explain the increase in borrowing during a recent investigation by the Commons Privileges and Standards Committee regarding his pre-borrowing arrangements.
The Committee cleared him last month of any charges of non-compliance, after an investigation into his expenses.
In 2004, Mr. Duncan changed the legal certainty of borrowing GBP 271.406 from his London property at his constituency house, which he purchased in 1991, the year before becoming a member of parliament.
The documents published this week show that Mr Duncan claimed about GBP 1,400 per month of interest on loans until March of last year.
In April, its requests increased by more than GBP 1,800 per month.
The interest rate on Duncan's RBS loan was not changed at that time, suggesting that all increases were intended to finance the GBP 75,000 loan.
The RBS variable standard interest rate rose from 7.94 per cent in December 2007 to 4 per cent in March this year, without moving since then.
The latest publication by the Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan continued to apply for GBP 1,250 in May.
Duncan lost his position as head of the ghost cabinet in September, after an undercover journalist allegedly filmed him saying that members of parliament had to survive "on budget" after the expense scandal.
"In fact, it's now national, you have to live "on budget" and you're treated as "de la m...e"
He said, "I spent my money on my garden and I asked for a small part, based on what was right.
and I could have asked for more, but I didn't."
The member of parliament, a millionaire since his former post as an oil trader, began to explain his expenses in May, after it became apparent that he had requested thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the office that this "could be considered excessive".
An activist dug a £-shaped hole in Duncan's lawn to protest after it was revealed that he had applied for GBP 4,000 for three years.
Asked about the increase in borrowing last night, Mr. Duncan said: "It was for major improvements, approved both by the fee office and then by Legg."
He added: "There's no problem with robbing or developing or using rules or anything.
It was quite clear, in the rules, authorized, etc.
It couldn't be clearer or simpler."
Faithful, come and see the calendar of Brighton Advent.
Brighton beach cabins have found a new way to promote the winter months, an interactive Advent calendar.
Beyond, an alternative church group that encourages spiritual exploration through creativity, invited 24 owners to decorate their cabin for each day of December, using Christmas songs as a theme.
The event began on December 1st, while visitors were allowed to visit the last cabin, from 5:30 p.m. to 6:30 p.m., each day, with free blocks and hot wine.
Christmas songs chosen so far include "I Saw Three Ships, O Come, O Come, Emmanuel and The First Christmas", for which the booth presents the work of Janette Tozer, a local artist.
Martin Poole, 50, a TV marketing assistant from Hove, is an unpaid priest from the diocese of Chichester and Director of Beyond.
He said: "We want religion to be closer to people in a post-Christian society.
"As a Church, why do we expect people to enter a strange old building? It seems to me that the Church should get closer to people and celebrate in a more captivating way.
