The history-geo emerges strengthened from the reform of the general high school, according to Chatel
The Minister of National Education Luc Chatel said in an interview to be published in the JDD on Sunday that history and geography were "enhanced" from the reform of the general high school, despite the abolition of their compulsory education in scientific terminal.
From now on, first class students will all have four hours a week and the same program for a shared common culture, says Chatel.
For the minister, "we have to get out of hypocrisy" because, according to him, "S is no longer a scientific sector" but "in general, it concentrates the best students".
The ES and L channels cannot remain sub-wires of the S, he continues, stressing again: "I have also not heard many historians and intellectuals indignant at the absence of the history-geography at the terminal in the technological high schools".
On Saturday, an Ifop poll published in L'Humanité revealed that nearly seven out of ten French (69%) disagreed with the government's plan to eliminate the compulsory teaching of history-geography in terminal S. Many intellectuals and teachers also criticized this suppression, as well as the left and some elected from the right.
On the other hand, the minister added that there was no "no way" to remove the philosophy of the S terminal program.
Luc Chatel also defended the reform of teacher training, while 16 organisations (students and trade unions) called for a day of mobilization on Tuesday to protest against the project, which in their opinion sacrifices the pedagogical training of future teachers.
In Master 2 (M2), they will pass an eligibility test at the beginning of the year that will focus on their discipline, and then at the end of the year an admission test that will focus on their ability to teach, said the Minister.
They will also attend internships during the year of M2 and then be a first year in front of students as trainee teachers.
If you add up all the internships offered before the competition, you already get more attendance in front of the students, i.e. more than 300 hours, he continued.
Finally, the Minister said that he would propose "the individual right to training, which does not exist in national education".
It also reaffirms the plan to delete the school card "by 2012".
