Liliane Bettencourt case: François-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of weakness
The court of Nanterre decided on Friday to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine whether, as the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt accuses him, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenary to deprive her of part of his fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his star photos, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by up to three years' imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga on one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear each other apart while holding the reins of the cosmetics empire L'Oréal.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical examination of Liliane Bettencourt, 87 years old, should be conducted collegiately by three doctors.
The heiress and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, at least not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre prosecutor's office during the investigation.
Designated physicians on Friday will be required to submit a report by March 10, 2010, stating in particular whether Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness and at what times.
I think she'll do it.
I'm going to talk to her about it, and she told Ms. Bettencourt's lawyer, Mr. Georges Kiejman, at the end of the hearing.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers's lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news (...) The expertise will demonstrate that he (Mr.Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who must be protected, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has brought criminal charges against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and a touch-to-all artist, whom she accuses of having taken advantage for years of her mother's weakness to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
Liliane Bettencourt, for her part, has always refuted having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers to be a long-time friend.
While the court had to consider the admissibility of the action brought by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' pleadings sometimes turned to great family unpacking on Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Can you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I've never been able to talk to her since her marriage."
For its part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office again held that the complainant was not entitled to take action, especially since in recent days a guardianship judge refused to grant her application to initiate judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to act in court, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in her place," said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the big French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the management attitude of large companies towards its employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was formerly, of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires on the part of employees a commitment that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns on the same footing as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally, after many detours, gets to do first and foremost... what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
Coming from the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the United States 'neurosciences' and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, inappropriate to the world today.
Identify and measure drivers of engagement
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment for the company is only possible if it is clearly seen as a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
At present, only the studies resulting from the Functional Pattern Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the business, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilising factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and hand over their human resources management "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: "Just War" Worth Right Praise to Obama
On Friday, the American right welcomed Barack Obama's previous speech in Oslo, who was satisfied that the Nobel Peace Prize 2009 defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who brokered the award to Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice-president in the 2008 elections.
I liked what he said, said Mrs Palin, the right wing geriatric of the Republican Party, in the daily USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the topic of war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is, of course, the last thing I think Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped there, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 additional soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, felt that the president had done "very good work" in Oslo.
I found the speech to be very good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, was delighted to have seen "a leftist president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and would not be able to award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former George W. Bush converti columnist at the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it", said Mr Gerson.
Among the few on the right to be unconvinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN Ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as "ternal, ampoule and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed at Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we wrap war in the notion of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained laudable to the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was prematurely awarded to Obama, described his speech as "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression" has ignited the Californian daily.
Obama "made the right speech," said the New York Times, judging him "both gloomy and edifying."
Roads: three marathons for an agreement that saves Christmas supplies
After three negotiations-marathon sessions, the trade unions in the road sector and TLF, the only employers' organisation to have remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that puts an end to the slogan of strike and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, Secretary of State for Transport Dominique Bussereau "rejoiced" this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, started Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussion, the negotiators left in the early morning of Friday, hoping to sign the text of the agreement quickly at the end of the morning.
Even if three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting that started at 11:00 a.m. for everyone to agree and at 6:00 p.m. the text to be signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "there was a concern that it would disrupt the end-of-year celebrations," said Mr. Bussereau.
The text foresees a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wages (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low wages, "from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we're going from a long way, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
It's either we're going to order our militants that there's no blockade, no blockade of the food centres.
But we can still have some recalcitrants that are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, President of TLF, welcomed "a good deal", even though it was "difficult to concede increases on high wages in view of international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and from 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) referred to "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for an increase in travel costs of 3%, and the maintenance of general conditions for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will allow in particular to address the question of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the draft amending finance law for 2009, which was voted on the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in identical terms".
TLF's signature allows the agreement to be applied first to companies affiliated with this organisation, and second to the whole profession, in case of extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be "as soon as possible", said Mr Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupe market", as the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year, lamented the Unostra.
For the Otre, the agreement risks "to dig the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
