Turkish justice dissolves the pro-Kurdish party, a decision with serious consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court pronounced the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision which was immediately followed by demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-eastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision may greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "foyer of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", told the press the president of the Court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required for the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that 37 party leaders, including President Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "guidelines" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered as a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party assures that it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict of the Court comes at a time when the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, to try to stop Kurdish support for the PKK and to put an end to the conflict.
DTP leaders had claimed that dissolution could lead to renewed tensions in southeast Anatolian, where numerous demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the leader of the PKK Abdullah Öcalan have escalated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the courts announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP's premises in Diyarbakir, the large south-eastern city, populated mostly by Kurds.
Law enforcement fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while demonstrators threw molotov cocktails or stones, with fronds.
A hundred people also protested in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk asserted that the decision of the Justice would "enhanced despair".
Turkey cannot resolve this question (Kurdish, ndlr) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can, of course, expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sanding service (FES) says that it is not to bother the citizens.
It is simply so that agents can test the technique of vehicles and learn to master them well.
And according to the meterologists, it could be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to attack snow and ice.
The FES follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr Brauburger explains that as soon as he starts snowing on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles run 20 main routes (known as routes A).
This includes busy streets, main arteries such as Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire-fighting access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
FES officers begin duty at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometres of road must be salted with a well-adhesive road melt in up to 3 hours of time.
This is why the FES service begins at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder, it's when the snow starts falling at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the road clearing and sanding department "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it no longer snows, access roads and service roads - like the Rat-Beil-Straße - are taken care of.
Secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr Brauburger is well aware that this still causes a few complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES hiking team set off to clear priority areas deemed dangerous and passages.
As for bike paths, the services of the FES are generally unable to handle them.
Mr Brauburger said that there was a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of bridges between 22 o'clock and 0430.
Since ice is formed very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
The police may also call on this special service when necessary.
The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae looked like other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was equipped with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with claws in sickle and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin reports and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the supercontinental lands, the Pangea and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
In fact, he tells us about the relationship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team tells us that sometimes they find a dozen bones in one day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
The researchers named him Tawa after the word Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a very exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to some incomplete bone fragments.
Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it makes it possible to confirm certain theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the later tyrannosaure and the velociraptor, from which the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds in the long neck, and those related to them and the herbivores ornithisches, which include species such as triceratops and stegosaure.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of characteristics that are both primitive and developed, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found evidence that Tawa hallae had small airbags in its bones at the level of the skull, as well as birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small airbags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also possessed airbags and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the land that formed the Pangae Supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the paleontologist team also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, advance the researchers.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine said there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaure, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him this could give an erroneous view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while there are virtually no dinosaurs on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of present-day crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet thus promoting the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between Trias and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, dinosaurs were better suited and they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorite meteorite blossoming of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and which since then had been vegetating in the shade: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley, California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
