The new Silicon-valley
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place for the search for secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet Silicon Valley.
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As of September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, a place of francfort science – with the university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of Close Collaboration".
The signatories were Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz Head of Project Section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose main focus is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the rapidly expanding Russian market.
In contrast, Russian scientific companies wish to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
There are the Moscow Electrotechnical Institute, the large Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika firms.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literally translated "Green City") derives its name from the wooded hills at the heart of which the research centres are established.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The size of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, into a desperate chaos of construction sites for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 1980s.
The head-end stations, with lanes ending in the city, had a reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th-century transport technology that had the effect of a brake hoof of modern rail traffic because it used to take a long time to get the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that's what you have to do.
This is why the head stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train crossing station, which is about half way on the Trans-European Rail Magistral between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project is really going to begin, although the visions of the 1980s have long been incompatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, head-of-the-line stations are no longer a real problem of entry and exit since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and pilot car at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now being launched next to the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and communal policies have prevailed.
The railway company is in the party because it is the taxpayer who incurs the costs of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public enterprise.
From the urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
We get an urban space that – according to computer-generated planners’ graphs – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and the expansion of the section are designed for trafficking in persons, which was, and is typical of the 1980s, an enormous growth.
