75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fécondité et career professionnelle des femmes en Espagne", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of couple life and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not, and the type of job she is employed.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, push back entry into marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector."These data show that women in stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of a common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years respectively on average.
"Another distinction also emerges between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have completed middle- and upper-level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
