Emergency brake aid is now mandatory
As has been done with the ABS anti-lock brake system and as will be done with ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear impacts.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the brake pressure in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were unable to press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take advantage of its full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, by going back, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: one in four accidents with injured persons would be calculated to be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, by means of radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps him by increasing the pedal pressure, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts the maximum force on the brakes in order to minimize damage.
